        t_.put("((SCHNITTE)). SUBMITTED WERE 4 DIFFERENTLY STAINED SECTIONS FROM A LUNG LESION. IN HE-SECTIONS THERE IS A HYPERPLASIA OF BALT ALONG THE AIRWAYS AND FOCALLY THERE IS ALSO AN ACCUMULATION OF LYMPHOCYTES IN ALVEOLAR WALLS. IN ADDITION THERE IS ORGANIZING PNEUMONIA WITH GRANULATION TISSUE IN THE ALVEOLI AND IN BRONCHIOLS WITH THE TYPICAL FEATURE OF BRONCHIOLITIS OBLITERANS. IN SOME AREAS THERE IS A DESQUAMATION OF ALVEOLAR MACROPHAGES IN THE ALVEOLI AND IN THE AREA OF RESPIRATORY BRONCHIOLS VERY MUCH THE WAY AS IN RESPIRATORY BRONCHIOLITIS. IN ADDITION THERE IS MILD FIBROSIS ALSO IN ALVEOLAR WALLS AND IN SOME AREAS THERE IS AN INFILTRATION OF LYMPHOCYTES, RARELY GRANULOCYTES WITHIN THE ALVEOLAR LUMEN. IT TOOK ME A LONG TIME TO LOOK FOR THE DEVELOPMENT OF GRANULOMAS AND FINALLY I FOUND SOME AREAS WHERE YOU CAN SEE EPITHELOID CELL TRANSFORMATION WHEREAS GIANT CELLS ARE MUCH MORE SCATTERED ALL OVER THE LUNGS. THE GRANULOMAS WHICH HAVE DEVELOPED ARE VERY LOSELY, NOT WELL CIRCUMSCRIBED, NOT THE SARCOID TYPE. THE GIANT CELLS IN THEIR MAJORITY ARE FOREIGN BODY GIANT CELLS, HOWEVER A FEW LANGHANS GIANT CELLS HAVE ALSO DEVELOPED. I COULD NOT PERFORM IMMUNHISTOCHEMISTRY BECAUSE I DIDN'T HAVE UNSTAINED SECTIONS AT HAND. FROM THE MORPHOLOGICAL DESCRIPTION POINT THERE ARE 3 PROCESSES: LOSELY CIRCUMSCRIBED HISTIOCYTIC AND EPITHELOID CELL GRANULOMAS, A LYMPHOID HYPERPLASIA WITH FOLLICAL FORMATION IN THE SENSE OF FOLLICULAR BRONCHIOLITIS BUT ALSO SOME AREAS OF LYMPHOCYTIC INTERSTITIAL INFILTRATION, NOT TO AN EXTEND THAT YOU WOULD CALL IT LYMPHOID CELL INTERSTITIAL PNEUMONIA. THEN THERE IS ORGANIZING PNEUMONIA AND IN ADDITION THERE IS RESPIRATORY BRONCHIOLITIS - INTERSTITIAL LUNG DISEASE. NOW HOW TO INTERPRET? WITH RESPECT TO COLLAGEN VASCULAR DISEASES I DON'T THINK THIS REACTION PATTERN FITS INTO ANY OF THE CATEGORIES OF COLLAGEN VASCULAR DISEASE. ORGANIZING PNEUMONIA AND LYMPHOID HYPERPLASIA IS SOMETIMES SEEN IN RHEUMATOID ARTHRITIS INVOLVING THE LUNG AND IT IS ALSO SEEN IN SOME CASES OF DERMATOMYOSITIS. HOWEVER, RESPIRATORY BRONCHIOLITIS TO MY KNOWLEDGE HAS NEVER BEEN DESCRIBED IN THIS SETTING. SLE CAN PRESENT ITSELF AS ORGANIZING PNEUMONIA, HOWEVER, IN MY EXPERIENCE YOU ALWAYS SEE SOME PRECEEDING FEATURES, WHICH POINT TO DIFFUSE ALVEOLAR DAMAGE WHICH IS THEN FOLLOWED BY ORGANISATION INTO THE MORPHOLOGICAL PICTURE OF ORGANIZING PNEUMONIA. THERE IS NO LYMPHOID HYPERPLASIA AT LEAST TO MY KNOWLEDGE. NOW GOING TO EAA: LYMPHOID HYPERPLASIA AND ORGANIZING PNEUMONIA AS WELL AS LYMPHOCYTIC INTERSTITIAL INFILTRATES FOCALLY SCATTERED ALL OVER THE LUNG IS NOT UNUSUAL AND THE GRANULOMATOUS REACTION FITS WELL INTO THIS PICTURE. WHAT MAKES A PROBLEM IS THE RESPIRATORY BRONCHIOLITIS PATTERN, WHICH I HAVE NOT SEEN IN EXTRINSIC ALLERGIC ALVEOLITIS. HOWEVER, I REMEMBER A CASE OF ISOTHIOCYANATINHALATION, WHICH SHOWED A SIMILAR DESQUAMATIVE REACTION IN THE PERIPHERAL LUNG AS I SEE IT HERE AND ISOTHIOCYANAT-INDUCED EXTRINSIC ALLERGIC ALVEOLITIS PRESENTS ITSELF IN A SIMILAR PICTURE AS THE CLASSICAL EAA. SO I ALSO WOULD FAVOR EAA IN THE FINAL INTERPRETATION OF THIS REACTION. HOWEVER, I WOULD SUGGEST TO MAKE IMMUNOHISTOCHEMISTRY FOR CD 4 AND CD 8 LYMPHOCYTES AS WELL AS B-LYMPHOCYTES. THERE SHOULD BE A CONCENTRATION OF CD 8-SUPPRESSORCELLS IN THE GRANULOMATOUS AREAS WHEREAS THE CD 4-HELPER LYMPHOCYTES SHOULD BE MORE CONCENTRATED ALONG THE LYMPHFOLLICLES. B-LYMPHOCYTES CAN BE SCATTERED BUT SHOULD BE CONCENTRATED MORE OR LESS IN THE LYMPHFOLLICLE CENTRES. ANOTHER WAY WOULD BE TO DO A LAVAGE AND TO LOOK FOR THE CD 4/CD 8 RATIO.", "");
